MATCH_TOOL: Edit|Write
MATCH_PATTERN: (buildSilverPayload|sendSilver|SEND_SILVER)
ADVISORY: |
  SEND_SILVER client-emit contract: the payload MUST NOT carry `channelId` (or
  legacy `channel`). The server resolves the target channel via
  `resolveExistingChannel(channels, event)`, which looks for an existing DM/GROUP_DM
  between sender and target and explicitly SKIPS MAIN-type channels.

  This matters because MAIN now carries the `SILVER_TRANSFER` capability
  (Plan A, commit be08602). If a client ever emits `channelId: 'MAIN'` on a
  SEND_SILVER event, `isSilverTransferAllowed` will authorize silver-in-MAIN —
  a flow no product decision has enabled.

  Canonical emit helper (keep pure, no channelId):
    apps/client/src/hooks/useGameEngine.ts → buildSilverPayload(amount, targetId)
    Returns: { type: Events.Social.SEND_SILVER, amount, targetId }

  Regression test (do not delete without replacing):
    apps/client/src/hooks/__tests__/silverRouting.test.ts — asserts no `channelId`,
    no `channel`, minimal shape.

  If you're adding a new silver-emit call site, use `buildSilverPayload` (or route
  through `engine.sendSilver`) rather than hand-rolling a WS message. If a new
  surface needs silver-in-a-specific-channel semantics, raise it with the user
  before emitting `channelId` on SEND_SILVER — it's a server-auth change in
  disguise.

  Source: docs/superpowers/specs/2026-04-13-pulse-dm-polish-design.md §Architecture
  ("Accepted consequence: server now authorizes SEND_SILVER with channel: 'MAIN'.
  Client discipline: `/silver` picker always resolves to a DM channel before firing.").
